> **Strategic Takeaway:** The plan sounds flawless. A customer encounters an issue. They search the knowledge base. They find the exact steps to solve the problem. They fix it themselves. The reality looks entirely different. When documentation becomes a wall, users walk away. A founder spends three weeks writing fifty articles explaining every corner of the application. Six months later, support requests remain high. The analytics dashboard shows the help center receives almost zero traffic. The documentation exists to serve the business, not the user. ## The failure of the encyclopedia approach No customer wants to read a manual. They want to accomplish a single task right now. Traditional knowledge bases fail because they force the user to leave the product. A customer encounters an error on the checkout page. They must open a new tab. They navigate to a separate help center. They search for the error code. They read five paragraphs of context before finding the solution. The effort required to find the answer exceeds the effort required to send a support email. This friction destroys the value of the documentation. The user chooses the path of least resistance. They email the support team. The founder wasted three weeks writing a manual nobody reads. ## A three-step method to fix useless documentation You must stop writing articles nobody reads. You need to identify what users need and put it in front of them. ### Step 1: Surface content where the problem happens Move the answer to the point of friction. Do not hide explanations in a separate portal. If users constantly fail to format a CSV import correctly, place the required template and instructions directly on the import screen. A single, well-placed tooltip solves more problems than a comprehensive thousand-word guide. The user needs the context immediately. They do not want to hunt for it. When the answer lives next to the problem, the user fixes the issue themselves. The support queue shrinks. ### Step 2: Gauge real usage Stop measuring page views. Track resolution rates. A high bounce rate on a help article means nothing. Did the user find the answer and leave, or did they give up in frustration? You must add a simple feedback mechanism to every guide. A button asking "Did this solve your problem?" provides clear data. If an article has a low resolution rate, the documentation failed. If an article has zero views in ninety days, delete it. Tracking the right metrics exposes the truth. You learn which features confuse users. You learn which explanations fail to clarify the process. ### Step 3: Update only what matters Your software changes faster than your ability to document it. Outdated instructions frustrate customers more than missing instructions.

